Subject:    <a href="?t=95837888800009&r=1&w=2">Domain database problems</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837784200026&r=1&w=2">Peter Karp &lt;KARP () SUMEX-AIM ! STANFORD ! EDU&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198703">1987-03-05 12:05:49</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926784&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926784&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Given the frequency with which these problems are starting to arise,
and will no doubt continue to arise, I think it's crucial to start
thinking of heuristics which can be used to help enforce database
consistency and correctness.

Not being a database maintainer myself, not many spring to mind, but
I will suggest the following:

If a server delegates authority for another domain to another server,
then an address record for that server MUST accompany the SOA record.

And how about this: perhaps servers should periodically check that
when they delegate authority, that they are able to contact at least
one of the servers to which authority is delegated, and have a query
answered.  Perhaps servers should check this every night.

In general I think this system is going to fall appart if it relies
exclusively on the correctness of the entries made by the thousands
of people who maintain it.  We've already seen how easy it is for people
to enter incorrect information due to misunderstandings of the system,
and due to oversights.

Peter
